FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE - ALGERIA (07): SEROTYPE O, SPREAD, CONTROL, VACCINATION
*******************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Sun 10 Aug 2014
Source: El Watan [in French, machine trans. summarised, edited]
http://www.elwatan.com/actualite/18-wilayas-touchees-par-la-fievre-aphteuse-10-08-2014-267532_109.php


The spread of the foot and mouth [FMD] epidemic continues across the country, affecting 18 wilayas [departments, out of the country's 48] until yesterday [Sat 9 Aug 2014], especially in the east and center of the country, since its inception on 25 Jul 2014, according to Boughalem Karim, Director of Veterinary Services in the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development.

The most affected wilayas are Setif, Bouira, Bejaia, Tizi Ouzou and Bordj Bou Arreridj. The 1st outbreak was recorded in Bir El Arch (Setif) following the fraudulent introduction of fattening calves from Tunisia. Two weeks later, the virus caused 192 recorded outbreaks out of the 200 000 cattle holdings; 964 cows and bulls affected by this disease, which is very dangerous for ruminants, have been slaughtered.

"These numbers are not catastrophic," said Karim Boughalem during a press conference at the headquarters of the ministry. Since its detection, the government has implemented a series of measures: sequestration of farms, banning the movement of animals, closure of livestock markets nationwide and vaccination of infected households.

"These measures are temporary. They will be lifted as soon as the disease is under control," said the Secretary General of the Ministry, Fodhil Feroukhi. The annual vaccination campaign, which was terminated on 30 Mar 2014, covered 850 000 cattle. In addition, some 757 000 animals have been vaccinated by the veterinary services since the appearance of the disease in May 2014 in Tunisia. Both vaccination programs have reached 75 to 80 percent of the cattle, a total of 1.6 million head [see comment regarding vaccine strain]. Veterinary services await the arrival this week of 900 000 doses of vaccine imported to expand the operation to all cattle.

To prevent the spread of disease and mortality of animals, the Department requires farmers not to move their animals except to the nearest abattoir, not to attend livestock markets, not to introduce new animals in their farms and to systematically quicklime at the entrance of the farms, banning the entry of foreigners on their holdings. The department has mobilized nearly 10 000 veterinarians to monitor the said preventive activities on farms.

After denouncing the attitude of some irresponsible breeders and horse dealers attracted by "greed," the 2 officials have launched an appeal to all stakeholders to strictly implement the prescribed measures and to inform the nearest veterinary office of any suspected cases. "The disease could be confined to Bir El Arch, in Setif, if farmers had made the necessary declarations," said the Director of Veterinary Services.

Animal owners whose livestock is affected will be compensated for 80 percent of the real price of slaughtered animals, provided they have duly declared. The rest (20 percent) will be covered after the slaughter and sale of the meat approved edible and safe for consumption. Questioned further about the impact of this disease on milk production and quality of meat, Fodhil Ferroukhi said production may drop due to the killing of a number of dairy cows. However, this epidemic will, according to him, have no impact upon either the quality or the price of red meat.

--
